ce:section.ce:para:
High-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HRTEM) image of GQDs is supported in Fig. S3. The nanoscale morphologies of the bare NiCo2S4 NWAs and the hierarchical-like GQDs/NiCo2S4 nanocomposites are exhibited by TEM (Fig. 3
                     ) and EDX mapping (Fig. 4
                     ). As shown in Fig. 3A and B, the NiCo2S4 NWAs feature solid smooth nanowire with an average diameter of about 200 nm. As additionally indicated in Fig. 3C, the complex nanostructure of the GQDs/NiCo2S4 nanocomposites is composed of hollow core and branch nanoflakes, forming a hierarchical-like hollow nanostructure. Compared with the smooth surface of the NiCo2S4 nanowire, such unique 3D hierarchical-like structure greatly enhances the surface area, offers vast redox reaction sites, which are beneficial for the enhancing electrochemical performance. Moreover, the unique hollow structure is also favorable for relaxing the volume expansion and alleviating the structure damage during cycling process. The HRTEM image of the GQDs/NiCo2S4 nanocomposites shown in Fig. 3D exhibits that the GQDs are evenly combined with NiCo2S4 particles. The EDX mapping image of a single GQDs/NiCo2S4 nanocomposite is presented in Fig. 4. The elemental mapping of C (Fig. 4A) demonstrates that the GQDs are distributed uniformly in the nanocomposites and accounts for a small share in comparison with other elementals mapping. The elemental mappings of the Co (Fig. 4C) and S (Fig. 4D) confirm the occurrence of the hollow nanostructure.
